The menu of a child with obesity: No breakfast, sausage for dinner
More than one third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with being overweight, with 9 percent of all students and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Recent surveys have shown that children with obesity are more likely to come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This shows once again how important the environment in which a person grows up and the examples around him are for his healthy development.
The tables of obese children are half as likely to have sausages on the table as those of normal-weight children.
More than 19 percent of the overweight children had fries for dinner the day before the "Obesity Is Not an Accident" education campaign.
In families with fat children, sports are not exactly a favorite activity, but so are the majority of today's students - only 15 percent said that their parents find time for active exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted towards the end of the school year last year, and involved nearly 900 children from primary schools throughout the Czech Republic.
This was the second year of the 'Obesity is not a coincidence' campaign, which is supported by the General Health Insurance Fund and Unilever.
So far, more than 12 thousand students from 4th and 8th grades have participated in the project.
Unhealthy diet and lack of exercise in the family are key factors in the alarming increase in the number of overweight or even obese children.
"For example, only half of the children surveyed said that they ate breakfast, lunch, dinner, and dinner five times a day - one of the main requirements for a healthy diet", says one of the results of the survey.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that even relatively small things, such as regular family breakfast, are important for a child's healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of the students' families have breakfast.
And in most families, everyone has their own breakfast.
The worst finding was that one in ten families does not have breakfast at all.
Breakfast is considered the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
The survey revealed that unhealthy fries are consumed much more often in families with overweight children.
And almost everyone, regardless of their weight, drinks sugary lemonade every day (70 percent).
Although more than 40 percent of the children surveyed exercise, less than half of their parents do - only 15 percent.
Make your own menu
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to make their own meal plans based on their appetite and opinion.
"The Czech children's preferences for nutrition between 12 and 15 are far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among her favorite foods were many flour dishes, meat dishes, and, of course, sweets.
"The alarming thing is the popularity of sweet sodas", the final report of the survey emphasizes.
At lunchtime, the main course, pasta was just ahead of chicken.
The children were almost averse to legumes, and the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes for lunch was very low.
Return to health
At the same time, the survey also showed that children are quite willing to change their eating habits if they are given the right information.
"In the control group of respondents who completed the questionnaire after the lecture 'Obesity is not a coincidence', a significant shift in preference towards principles of healthy eating was observed in many cases", the project results state.
This was evident, for example, in the sweet lime trees, where many children began to prefer plain water.
The children also had a much higher incidence of choosing poultry or fish as the main course of the day, and were willing to eat less dumplings or sweets.
