V Need for Speed: The Run - the illegal race across America
The review
The originally careless drive becomes a routine drive for the early shift through a series of completely avoidable, dilettante mistakes.
The ambitions were largely met, but what good was it if nobody was willing to do a little more?
Even before it hit the stores, the new episode, subtitled "The Run", was eliciting high expectations.
He promised to take the old Need for Speed series to a new dimension, and in the playable demo examples, it actually didn't seem to be just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious about the customized passages where the main character gets out of the car and walks on.
But as you're used to with NFS, things are much different than you expected.
Sure - potentially they're pretty decent arcade races, but overall the game is diminished by some superfluous bugs that have been present in this series for more or less a few years.
So they're not really bugs anymore, but rather signs of a fundamentally incomprehensible laziness on the part of game developers.
The adventure is off to a great start.
For the first time, you are introduced to the story, whose main character Jack has certain personal problems; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, on the West Coast, you get behind the wheel, and the task is to be the first to New York.
The basic idea involves a whole series of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is held on a different track and that each stage takes place in a different, sufficiently different and interesting environment.
You don't get the impression for a moment that the game is always offering the same thing over and over again.
Some environments are still very beautiful, although the technical level of the graphics does not exceed that of the earlier parts of the series.
So nothing that moves the world.
But driving through the desert, through autumn landscape, or high up through deeply snow-covered landscape is visually very pleasant.
Occasionally, unusual elements bring a little variety to the individual races.
In the desert, for example, you are surprised by a desert storm that severely limits your view.
In the mountains, you have to be very careful not to get hit by an avalanche.
In addition, the individual races are quite well integrated.
Just a few, but enough.
For a while you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to catch up (classic race against the stopwatch), then you are still waiting for a personal duel with a single opponent.
And then the police get involved and try to screw it up.
A novelty is the passages where Jack leaves the car.
It's more about certain interactive animations where Jack is running from someone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
Surprisingly, there are far fewer such passages in the game than one would expect (only three, in fact).
In the end, this is more to the advantage of the thing, because at least this element has no chance of becoming boring - it is one of the elements that make the game more varied in the context of the above.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of the previous parts.
That is to say, from today's point of view, it does not uproot trees, but on the other hand, you could not say that it was bad.
If you're looking for realistic simulations, you'll have to look elsewhere.
But the local model still fits the action-packed racing scene quite well, although you could find better ones in the competition.
Until then, everything is in order.
Real problems only come up after a while.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model isn't exactly OK.
You can't expect a game like this to calculate complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have no idea how the car behaves before you hit anything, then obviously everything is not right.
Typical example: When passing or overtaking oncoming cars, you may "run" the other cars lightly in some places, but in other, almost identical situations you may get into a sling and spin wild pirouettes.
Or the car goes to waste.
Thanks to the restart system, it's no big deal, but it's annoying all the time.
The restarts are arranged like this: if you have total damage or land far off the track, then the game throws you back to the last clue point of the track.
- Only in each race you only get five restarts.
Once you've exhausted them, everything starts again.
So the restarts are more like a tool in case something doesn't work, but you shouldn't rely on it.
Sometimes even a restart doesn't help, because the only thing that helps is memorizing the critical section.
What's really unpleasant is that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some curves have to be done in a very specific way, otherwise you just don't fit through.
Elsewhere, you will encounter "civil" cars at the appropriate location, always in the same configuration, whether you are first or fifth, five seconds early or a minute late.
This is especially annoying in situations where you see your opponent passing two cars in front of you playing, but by the time you get there, the cars are already in a position where you have to go around them or brake.
And it doesn't matter when you get there, because everything is designed to come to this situation right in front of your eyes.
The competitors have other advantages.
There are a few places in the game where you're always overtaken by the same opponent at the same spot and again here regardless of the time.
The craziest part is at the end of the game, on the long bridge, which you pass in the opposite direction.
The opponent must obviously overtake you here on the come out.
And when it's in front of you, it's obviously taking your view, so you're going to have to drive your own car a few times in a row.
- Of course you want to make the game more exciting and exciting, but that intention is so clear that it quickly deprives you of the joy of the game.
And that's a shame, because despite the simpler driving model, the game is quite entertaining overall and in some cases so action-packed that you almost don't know where your head is.
And it doesn't really matter what the "guilt" is - the concept of 50 unique routes, the arrangement of the races in such a way that you can't get bored, or something else entirely...
Another unusual idea is the change of car during the race.
You must not overlook the gas stations along the way, because this is where you can change cars, although in most cases the car you have is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for urban areas, the strong American limousines for the straight highways and exotic super sports cars for the technical rides, for example on the mountain serpents.
Hand in hand with the story mode of the game is the task mode (challenges) - the races in the individual locations you know from the story.
Here there are not only medals, but also experience points to win for your own profile, which is common for the tasks (challenges) and the story.
To get to the higher driver level, various items must be unlocked, starting with the car, to the background for the profile.
This is also linked to the online Autolog function, which compares the results of the player with those of other players and also provides for further collective functions.
Another of the most incomprehensible sculptures is a situation in the last race of history.
Here you drive into a subway tunnel (for me) where you race along the tracks in the dark (for me).
The speedometer shows a figure of 150 to 200 km/h (for me), but then suddenly a subway comes from behind and drives you to scrap.
I think we're gonna be in the newsroom arguing for a long time about whether this was a game developer blackout or whether the writers think we're so stupid.
The technical side is not overwhelming, but at least the overall visual impression is quite appealing in most cases and even brilliant here and there.
What's even more annoying is that at some exciting moments, the replay rate slows down, and sometimes quite dramatically.
This is particularly true of accidents involving a large number of persons, where continuous FPS is of no use.
The sound reproduction is fine as far as I'm concerned, and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to appeal to as broad a scale as possible to a younger audience, a soundtrack was created a lá "something from everyone" - but who buys such a game for the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run is a little mixed.
If the game hadn't been diminished by the totally unnecessary mistakes mentioned, we could have argued with the crest of conviction that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But it makes the game look kind of unfinished.
It's a great pleasure in itself, but you should be prepared for these mistakes to stick in your eyes with the power of airport lights.
Concert of the "Students of the Velvet Revolution" with the singing ensemble of the Charles University
The Festa Academica festival is now offering for the third time the merging of the World Student Day with the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution and this with a musical experience.
During the festival, the twenty professional and university choirs will introduce themselves.
The festival will focus on the two concerts on November 17.
"Charles University is a big part of the festival".
"The choir of the Faculty of Education and the Faculty of Humanities is also represented among the participants, and the festival committee includes Rector Václav Hampl", explained the head of the organizing team, Jakub Čaloun.
The highlight of the festival is the public concert of the school choirs, which will take place on 17 November at 2 p.m. on the square in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The programme includes the composition "Celebration Jazz Mass" by the great Czech jazzman Karel Růžička.
In the evening, the concert "Students of the Velvet Revolution" (Studenty sametu) takes place in the gallery rooms of the People's House in Vinohrady, where university choirs also perform, choirs of Charles University are not excluded.
Festa Academica aims not only to celebrate World Student Day and the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but also to present choral music to the public at the highest level and to promote the creative collaboration of young people.
The main organiser is the Association of Czech Choral Choirs in cooperation with the Johannes Kepler Gymnasium.
The whole event was sponsored by Bohuslav Svoboda, the mayor of the capital city of Prague, and Václav Hampl, the rector of Charles University.
The festival will take place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and Pardubice.
The programme includes, in addition to festival concerts, numerous music meetings, student events, matinees and other events.
For more information, please visit the festival's website www.festaacademica.cz
