Brand story:
The innovator IBM enters its second century of existence
If you were to look for a suitable word that most accurately characterizes IBM's strategy, it would be the word "longevity".
For the general public, IBM is synonymous with the technological revolution, known as a modern company, even though it has been a century since its founding.
The foundation for this longevity was laid by its first chief, the visionary Thomas J. Watson.
He already had the slogan that countless world problems could be easily solved if people were willing to think a little bit.
His slogan "Think!" became the trademark around which the life of the future giant was to unfold (and at the same time the title of the company's magazine, which began to be published at IBM as early as 1935).
This was also the basis for the company culture thoroughly prepared by Watsen.
"For us at IBM, this long-term thinking means a continuous movement towards the future.
