Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five authorised state travel agencies in the then Czechoslovak Soviet Union: Čedok, Sporttourist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies then mainly sold only trips to the socialist Eastern Bloc countries, whereas in the West only selected people were allowed to travel.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea, and to Hungary on the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when travel to Yugoslavia was also allowed, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that not even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (i.e. Czechoslovaks) were allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
If a citizen of the USSR, for example, wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he would need a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Even then, travel agencies offered trips to the West, but then you had to buy giant snakes or sleep in a sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, the matter had not gone well.
The so-called foreign exchange guarantee - the condition for traveling to the West - was granted only to people "politically reliable" - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czech currency was not a freely convertible currency, so without a foreign exchange guarantee it would have been impossible to raise the necessary funds (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
So the vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in the country, and it is no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend homes and cottages - a practice that continues to this day.
The Velvet Revolution of 1989 was followed by a tourist revolution in the Czech Republic.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries all over the world.
A huge paradox, which is no longer noticed, is the fact that until 1989 you could not travel to the most popular Czech holiday destination - Croatia, because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
From the beginning of the 1990s, the foreign exchange requirement was abolished in the neighbouring countries of Western Europe, which led to a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
For a long time, Czechoslovaks could not get enough of their travels to the West, and everyone wanted to be there for at least a few days.
So the Czech holidaymakers slept in tents in the park when they went to Paris, because who would have had the money for a hotel or a boarding house back then?
A typical feature of foreign trips by Czechs at that time was a trunk full of canned goods, beer and sausages, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely convertible Czech krone - after decades, our tourists were finally able to buy Western currency freely.
Our standard of living and, consequently, average wages rose, which ushered in another important moment in 1997.
The increased demand for travel led to travel agencies starting to regularly prepare travel by charter flights after 1997, which made air travel incredibly cheaper than in the past thanks to the possibility of negotiating volume discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the USA, had already established currency-free payments with all the highly developed countries of the world, which made travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-velvet travel came in 2000, when the first direct charter flight to an exotic country - Thailand - was made thanks to high demand.
Since then, direct charter flights have been flying every year with Czech passengers to far-off sunny countries; this year, 12 exotic destinations are being flown directly from the Czech Republic.
Every year, 100 thousand Czechs travel to exotic countries!
Another significant moment in the epoch that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, which definitively ranked our country among the highly developed countries of the world.
In 2008, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad for the first time (50.3%) and for the first time in their history spent more than CZK 15 per head on a single holiday including the costs of the holiday destination.
