"I once wondered why swimming pools have to be so ugly", says the Vienna-based Meder.
So I started collecting beautiful baths.
Water surface doubled architecture
Suddenly in the swimming pool and essential sauna oils - the wellness factor in baths is so great because all the senses are served, says Meder.
And if the builders have put in the effort, swimming pools can be a real treat: "In places with floors, you have a surface".
"It is transparent on the one hand, but it reflects the beauty of the whole building on the other".
Everything doubles visually: high vaults, colorful tiles, bouncing boards.
The small-format booklet "Badefreuden" contains 190 pages of information on the architectural and cultural history of historic wellness oases - but above all it makes you want to take a leap into the blue.
Remarkable specimens were discovered by pool collector Meder during her research in Hungary.
In addition to magnificent spas, such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi Bath in Budapest, she found a nitrate-containing water in an ancient karst cave (a cave bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) and a thermal bath, whose pools are filled with alkaline water and are located in a bottle-shaped building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény).
In contrast, many heated outdoor pools in Switzerland and Austria offer spectacular views: While the Zurich rooftop pool offers a view of the entire city, the outdoor pool of a pool in St. Anton offers a view of the snow-capped Arlberg - and: The steam pool has a window from which you can watch the activity on the ski slope.
Perhaps the most extraordinary pool design awaits bathers in Längenfeld: The Aquadome Ötztal looks like a UFO that has just landed in the Alps.
In winter, it vaporizes from three open shells, while in the background the mountains of the Ötztal rise to the sky.
The Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not every pool collector's nose got the smell of chlorine.
Many thermal baths smell of sulphur, and the Árpád bath in Békescsaba, Hungary, smells of heating oil so strongly that you can hardly believe you've landed in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkaline hydrocarbon water, which is almost black and its glue sticks to your skin as soon as you slip into the pool - a special kind of wellness experience.
However, one place where Iris Meder was disappointed in her search for beautiful bathing spots was the Czech town of Bad Luhatschowitz, where she was planning to visit the outdoor and sunbathing area.
The bath, designed in 1902 by the architect Dušan Jurkovic, has since been closed.
As Meder glanced through the weathered windows of the red-white-yellow Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds growing among the tiles.
