21st house in Vienna
The relocated pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural story with highs, lows and happy endings: The Austrian pavilion at the 1958 Brussels World's Fair won prizes, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and decayed.
Now it's being reopened as an exhibition hall.
If the scene is full of modern post-war architecture, clear shapes, glass halls, bold swings and new building materials, typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion by architect Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 Brussels World's Fair is a striking and famous example.
Schwanzers Pavilion was awarded the Grand Prix d'Architecture for its lightweight and floating steel-glass construction.
The building is still considered a milestone of contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so known that he also built a pavilion at the next World Exhibition in Austria.
With his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus a bullet-like side-build in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
Its pavilion, which was planned as a temporary exhibition building, was erected after the World's Fair in the Swiss Garden at the Vienna South Railway Station, converted and in 1962 opened a museum of the 20th century - it was called the "20th House".
The building was neither spatially nor technically suitable as a museum - no walls to hang art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art in Vienna got a new home.
Since 2001, the building has been empty and coming down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21st House" and will be used in the future as a museum for contemporary art.
On Tuesday evening, the Belvedere Museum, to which the house belongs, opens its first exhibition - a lucky event in every respect.
The new beginning was set in motion by Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Belvedere Gallery in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, who had a distinguished career as an art historian, including a career as a young artist, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum of Modern Salzburg, insisted on the rebuilding of the building with politicians and conservationists, and obtained public and private sponsorship funds and fixed the use.
In addition to contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, a café and a bookstore were to be built, and an office building was to be built.
Strict supervision, small budget
For the execution, Krischanitz was the ideal cast.
Not only because he had sensitively rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich's Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but also because he had studied with Schwanzer at the Vienna University of Technology and the pavilion was an "extremely important place" for him, where he had seen the exhibitions "almost every weekend".
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which had already lost its grandeur and lightness when it was moved to Vienna and reused.
The current renovation was far more problematic: The building was "an energy waste", says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facade were replaced, fibreglass reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof replaced by special safety glass.
Cold-bridge steel supports have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been refurbished.
Two lower floors made room for the new use, a lowered light trench between the house and the street provides the lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light swans pavilion.
The original exterior doors are still there, the house is painted in the old reddish-brown rust-proof tint.
And the theater is still exactly as it was.
And all this under the strict supervision of the Monuments Authority and on a small budget.
"Often you had to find a material that was good and cheap and that the conservation office liked", says Krischanitz, pointing to a rusty floor in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and alterations, the building has remained flexible and light.
It was difficult with the pavilion, "which came from Brussels", Krischanitz recently said, a typical "drop-in-the-city story".
Such architecture is "always in the wrong place" and yet "seeks to awaken the right consciousness".
In this case, however, the 21st house is not in the wrong place, for an urban development event has occurred: around the Swiss garden is being built the completely newly planned "Hauptbahnhofsquartier", with office and residential buildings.
And another lucky event may come: the 21st house could be reinforced by another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg has bought the Berlin Temporary Art Hall, and it is reported that she is already negotiating with the city for a neighborhood location in the Swiss Garden.
