Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Watch You on Facebook
Before he became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just one of many guys who posted their anti-immigration views online.
Breivik, who confessed to a July massacre in Norway that killed 77 people, had his first public hearing in court on Monday.
Although Breivik may have acted alone, he is far from alone in cyberspace: he spent much of the time before his attack in front of his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on social networking sites.
After the tragedy this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
It's easy - you just have to log in to Facebook.
"We found that it was not difficult to reach them", says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report on digital populism in Europe by the British think tank DEMOS.
Facebook's concealment of personal data is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers simply need to use the site's advertising tool to pinpoint their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy - just as marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of right-wing extremist groups across Europe and then targeted them with ads, but instead of linking to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to a survey asking about their educational level, their attitude toward violence, and their own assessment of their future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without ever having to leave their offices.
"It's a fairly new research method", says Bartlett.
Some of the results are hardly surprising: online supporters of far-right groups are mostly young, male and angry about immigration.
But in a sort of surprising twist, "those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more rational, more democratic and less violent than those who sit behind their computer screens".
Demo's work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Ideas makers, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends like likes, text messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users, who add an average of three pieces of content a day, Facebook's "data supernova" is generating a research boom that has seen the number of scientific papers with the name of this page in the title increase by almost 800% over the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that you can study people through it that you wouldn't normally reach with your clipboard on the street.
"When you used to try to interview people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them".
"They had to inform the party first and they would never have given them access", says Bartlett.
"On Facebook, you lose all that -- you go straight to them".
Others say the site offers a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their binge drinking on Facebook were significantly more likely to have problem drinking than students who kept quiet about it.
Moreno suggests that peers, such as housing counselors, monitor the site and help a student if they post too many status updates.
"You can't solve a problem if you haven't recognized it", said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Morenos and director of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle, Washington.
"We have found a way to identify vulnerable children who would not otherwise have been found".
Facebook is also constantly tapping into the data of its own population.
The site's data team has compiled statistics on relationship status and Valentine's Day, voter turnout in the 2010 midterm elections, and a national happiness index (which primarily uses data only Facebook has access to - champions of digital freedom have long known that the site should make its big data mine available to others for research purposes).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them whether they want to or not, and in order to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, you allow the site to provide your personal data.
But what if Facebook users were to be part of a survey they didn't even know about?
While researchers have strict guidelines for how they collect their data offline, online everything is allowed.
"I don't think many users have even thought about the fact that a researcher might be studying their profiles", says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, of a 2006 study in which he studied the public pages of students on Facebook.
"As far as she was concerned, it was all about her and her friends".
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research participant is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how much of what is said in a user profile and in posts is true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things", says Selwyn.
So, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn still thinks that a clipboard and a pen are the best research tools anyone can use.
"There's no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people", he says.
"Social research has to be about social -- and a lot of social life is still happening offline".
