7 lessons from the late Steve Jobs interview that was shown in a theater this week
After Steve Jobs' death on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, highlighting the technological genius as a great modern inventor.
But what Apple fans may find most enlightening in the recently rediscovered Jobs interview, which was dusted off this week before special screenings in key markets, is how much this creative mind has understood business processes and workflows.
He was certainly a designer, a dreamer, and a self-styled hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer who made diagrams with a zeal - a man who believed that many CEOs suffered from "a disease of the mind", "that a really great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there's an enormous amount of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product".
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the TV series "Triumph of the Professional Idiots" about the rise of the personal computer, and he sat with Jobs for over an hour, in one of the rare, detailed conversations.
By this time, it had been 10 years since Jobs had been kicked out of Apple, and he was already hard at work on his new computer company, NeXT, and looking forward to the widespread adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringley's interview was used in "Specialists", he says the copy templates of the interview were missing on delivery.
It wasn't until after Job's death that a complete VHS copy was discovered in the principal's garage.
This slightly revised footage forms the basis for the 68-minute film "Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview", which is coming to Landmark theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone who is known to detest in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly eager to explain his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
Four times during the interview, there are longer pauses between question and answer - 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, during which Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts and strives for accuracy.
There are also moments when Job's perfectionism comes to light, when he seems impatient to respond to Cringley's questions, prompting him to move more quickly on issues or side-stories of greater importance.
Taken before the era of Pixar, iPod, or iPhone, the Lost Interview seems a bit far-sighted, when Jobs evaluates what other companies are doing right or wrong in his opinion and his own vision of the future of computing.
It's one thing to read posthumous reviews of Jobs' career, but to see Jobs here as the ambitious dreamer on the verge of greatness is something completely different, original and inspiring.
He has a vision of how things could and should be.
Shortly after he had done all this, he went and did it.
A quick look at seven remarkable sequences from the Lost Interview:
How he learned to run a business:
"All these years in business, I've always asked, 'Why do you do things?' And the answer you always get is, 'Oh, that's how it's done.'
Nobody knows why they do what they do. Nobody in business really thinks things through.
I've noticed that.
Jobs continues his efforts to streamline accounting at Apple.
Impressed by the way costs were recorded - usually starting with "standard costs" which were calculated on a guessing basis and then adjusted by "deviation" - he developed an automated factory that ensured that business costs could be determined down to the smallest detail.
As the Pope was vilified:
Jobs tells us about the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak, a device that you could use to sneak into the phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
Much has been written about the device, but Job's enthusiasm in describing the Blue Box as an act of self-empowerment is infectious.
He describes how he and Wozniak would test the box by using a pay phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while they sifted through as many satellites as possible.
"We sent stuff half a dozen times around the world, and if you'd just run it into the phone, it would come out in the next phone a minute later", Jobs said with a chuckle.
"We were young and we learned that we could build something ourselves that could control trillions of dollars of infrastructure around the world".
We didn't know much, but we were able to build this little thing that could control this huge thing, and that was an incredible lesson, and I don't think there would be an Apple without it.
Jobs goes on to tell of a glorious prank that he and Wozniak almost pulled off when they called the Vatican in the middle of the night via Blue Box to talk to the Pope while they were doing their best to emulate Henry Kissinger.
Since several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the American diplomat, they had to laugh before the pope himself answered the phone.
How he fell in love with technology (and unpreparedly called Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, when he was looking for spare parts to build a frequency meter, he looked for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone call, Jobs got a part-time job at Hewlett-Packard for the summer.
"It had a remarkable impact on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my views about what a company was and how well it treated its employees".
Later, Jobs became one of the HP employees who visited the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made".
It was the size of a suitcase, had a little screen with a brown tube, and I fell in love with it.
I would climb up to HP as a teenager and hang on to that machine and write programs for it.
How to improve innovation:
Several times in the interview, Jobs talks about how to spontaneously invent new products.
Early in his career, when he was assembling some boards, he was asked by a client to assemble the entire computer.
He worked with a payment period of only 30 days and had to think through both the assembly and the delivery of the finished equipment.
Later at Apple, he recalls the problems he had in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember some very strong arguments... they were yelling at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300] and I got up, went out and found a manufacturer".
And 90 days later, we had a mouse that we could have built for 15 dollars, which was incredibly believable.
About the big companies that are falling behind.
Long before he resurrected Apple, Jobs foresaw the ways in which so many industrial giants would stumble with their visions and lose control of their stocks.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make a better copier or printer, so what?"
They own the stock monopoly, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [these are the people] who ultimately run the companies and the product, who push people out of decision-making.
The product genius that has led to this monopoly position is being eradicated by people who have no concept of good products versus bad products - craftsmanship is necessary.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
You could have been ten times bigger, you could have been the Microsoft of the '90s...
You've taken defeat from victory.
On innovation as an art form:
"There's a lot of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product... when you develop that great idea, it changes and grows".
You learn a lot about its subtleties.
You have to do votes, certain things you can't do, but electrons, glass, robots, factories.
You have to remember 5,000 things, these concepts, and put them all together...
Ultimately it's all about taste, it's all about trying to sort of take the best stuff that humans have created and then trying to bring those things together into what you make.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We're always shameless in stealing great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh great was that the people who worked there were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who happen to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it hadn't been for the computer industry, they would have done fantastic things in other fields.
