How to Discover a Lie
A glance at the current headlines reveals how alarming and widespread deception and lying are in daily life.
The Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy dealing with allegations of sexual harassment by several women, both of whom accuse each other of lying.
The Penn State administration is accused of perjury for allegedly withholding reports that a retired football coach sexually abused boys.
Last week, an open microphone was used to overhear French President Nicolas Sarkozy telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weidner made a fool of himself by circulating denials that were quickly refuted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards is charged with campaign finance violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And then, of course, no one who has lived through it will forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton sparked when he lied in the Oval Office during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Stories of cheating at school and college are common.
There have been instances where teachers have given their students the test answers so that they themselves would get good marks on their tests.
Mentors who are supposed to teach the opposite send a message that lying and cheating are okay.
How much deception are we experiencing?
Studies show that we lie between 10 and 200 times a day.
But many of these lies are considered to be necessity lies.
Another study found that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Lying is an important skill for every person to learn, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a social game, such as charades, where the aim is to shout "Have you!" the cultivation of deception is a serious field of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that have carried out far-reaching research projects, particularly in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most of the old myths about lying have been debunked.
Lies look you in the eye.
They don't stutter, stutter, blush and stutter all the time.
But this does not mean that these liars are difficult to detect and disguise.
A trained lie detector can penetrate the truth by learning about the structure of the claim, the subtle facial expressions, the question mark and the timing.
I've spent several years studying the scientific results of the vast and ever-expanding field of disguise, and it's clear that disguise is a modern skill that's easy to learn and helps us to find our way in our complex world, especially when hiring or interviewing people or negotiating or managing is one of our professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at judging other people, at arousing their interest, at controlling their own emotions, and they intuitively sense how they are perceived by others.
Research shows that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men are more likely to tell "self-centered" lies than women, that men lie more "for others" - usually to protect their feelings - that married people lie less than single people (but the lies they tell are usually "big lies").
We also know that when a person is exposed as a criminal, others feel less guilty for lying to that person.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, by observing the normal behavior of this person.
This is called baselining, the starting position.
It provides a reference point for later evaluation of changes.
Observe the posture, the laughter, the quality of your subject's voice.
You should know better when someone is usually tripping all the time so that you don't falsely accuse them of tripping during a meeting.
Then watch for accumulations of conspicuous verbal and nonverbal behavior.
Consider these piles as alarm bells ringing, not evidence of a cover-up.
People who cheat may become numb as they try to remember their story, may point their feet toward the door or lean toward the exit, change their position in a significant way, or show a "post-interview relaxation", that deep, relaxed exhalation and shift in attitude when all the hard questions are over.
Askers often mistakenly signal that a job interview is over, only to look for the job interview after that relaxation.
Also, pay attention to the language of your subject.
Scott Peterson's slip is famous for using the past tense to claim his murdered wife was still alive and triggered a national search for her.
Deceptive persons may also use language that distances them, such as "I did not have a sexual relationship with this woman... Miss Lewinsky", or repeating a tricky question in its entirety.
The most common verbal cues are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when they answer a tricky question: "Well... to tell you the truth... as far as I know... to the best of my knowledge and conscience".
This makes the answer perceptive rather than objective, often setting off alarm bells.
There is no magic cure for disguising lies, but you can learn skills that make disguising possible.
These skills make it easier for anyone to avoid being a victim of fraud, both in their personal and professional lives.
