2011 will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa. It is the first year that Mario López Valdez, who calls himself the initiator of change and who has great hopes for economic growth, is in government. However, due to the climate adversities, there can be no talk of growth, but on the contrary, the main economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February not only caused losses in the millions in agriculture, but also placed tight limits on the growth of the public sector, causing an overall decline in economic activity of 3.6% in the first quarter. This is mainly due to the historical reduction in agricultural development of 31.16%, which had a slowing effect on other economic sectors.
According to a report on the effects of the frost, published by the Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development), 582 000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, of which 78.03% were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07% were partially destroyed, mainly vegetable, maize and chickpeas.
The decline in economic activity until November has caused unemployment to continue to rise in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter, as from January to March 55,053 residents of Sinaloa were unemployed, which corresponds to 4.53 percent of the working population. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28 percent and from July to September to 6.19 percent, resulting in 74 000 unemployed in Sinaloa, which is 18 969 more people than in the first quarter.
Lower liquidity
The unemployment in Sinaloa in that year is due to several factors: economist Gerardo López Cervantes, dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences at the Universidad Autónoma (UAS), comments that the policies of public institutions indirectly explain the growing unemployment.
"What we are seeing is an increase in unemployment, which is due to a number of factors, including liquidity losses in the marketplace as a result of the cuts in funds due to anti-money laundering legislation passed by Congress, because it is not easy for those who are illegally accumulating dollars to make them work for themselves, to invest them or to use them for anything else", he explained.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that the growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the country to look for work abroad, particularly in the United States, has decreased, partly because of the immigration problems and partly because it is difficult to find work there too.
Unpaid work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more difficult when one considers the high proportion of black labour, which according to INEGI comprises 60.38% of the employed in the country who work without paying into the social security funds.
The low wages of unemployment and undeclared work are the lowest in all of Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Insurance Institute) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Mexican governmental agency for work and social welfare).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos as of September, which is much lower than the national average of 7375 pesos.
Decline in ADI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and rising unemployment, 2011 saw the sharpest decline in foreign direct investment (FDI) in the last ten years, with an FDI of $630,597 from January to June, according to the Secretaría de Economía (State Economic Office), a decline of 87.74 percent compared with $5,143,312 in the same period the previous year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Governmental Agency for Economic Development) for its part recorded a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The debts
In view of the economic crisis, the Land Government applied to the National Congress in July for a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities to revive the economy.
Reactions
The first year of the government made it obvious to the representatives of the business community that Mario López Valdés was unable to govern.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of the Manufacturing Industry in Mexico), argued that no efforts were made in 2011 to harmonize the views of the different sectors, including the state government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa was really very poor this year. It has to be worked hard to regain the ground lost this year and in 2012 we have to double down. The efforts of everyone and especially the progress of the already well-coordinated government team have not been sufficiently coordinated", he explained.
Slow economic growth
Loredo López said that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year made the economic development of the country difficult and slowed down.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including frost. One of the main effects is a slowing economy that is not sufficiently mobile to generate an economic dynamic that could produce an acceptable flow of processes, products and services.
Re-defining vocation
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Mexican Employers' Association) in Sinaloa, said that the state had to be encouraged to become more dynamic in productive activities.
"In general, we have seen that work has been done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program to redefine the economic appeal and line of the country, because it is important to activate all the material and human resources of Sinaloa", he said.
There's a lot to do
The Chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that would steer the government's efforts in better directions.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme", he explained.
He stressed that the current government had made progress in the government.
"There are areas where you can say that the government has acted more comprehensively. What I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work to be done", he said.
