"We had already been in this situation in the last parliamentary term because the state did not have sufficient economic resources.The programmes continued and this year we had to acquire the funds that the state had not invested to participate in these programmes", he explained.
Although the public authorities are obliged to pay these funds, he commented that the Minister for Administration and Finance, , was requested to speed up the administrative work and pay the outstanding part as soon as possible.
"Nearly 12 million dollars are due, and even though the year is almost over, they haven't given us a penny".
The court approves the move to digital television in Mexico for 2015
The shift from analogue to digital signals is one of the most important changes in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) rejected the constitutional actions filed by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree, which requires the shift from analogue to digital signals to be postponed from 2021 to 2015, due to the absence of eight votes required to challenge the law.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, felt that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his powers when he issued the decree-law detailing the switchover to digital terrestrial television.
The decision rejected the constitutional debate initiated by the Senate, which did not receive the necessary qualified majority of eight votes to allow the court to decide on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality, thus keeping the law in force.
The draft lawsuit, drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed declaring the decree-law unconstitutional because the Comisión Federal de Telecomunicaciones (Cofetel) (Federal Commission for Telecommunications in Mexico) is responsible for the regulation of radio and television, and therefore the decree-law would be contrary to hierarchical principles and legal reservations.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero himself voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies filed constitutional complaints against the decree-law.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the complaint lodged by the Chamber of Deputies, without entering into the debate on the project, which was also the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his contribution, the Prime Minister expressed his disagreement with the arguments of the project, namely that the Land Government should not regulate the measures to be taken by the public administration by general regulations.
"I also don't think doing that would undermine the independence of the regulatory body", she said, recalling that the central government is constitutionally responsible for planning strategic policy areas, such as the telecommunications sector, because it is the central government that runs state affairs.
The replacement of analogue signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes that has taken place around the world in recent years, resulting in better use of the radio spectrum, improved signal quality and more channels.
Postponing the switchover, she said, was a postponement of the benefits of digitisation, a decision in the public interest that had not only technical aspects, 'because it covers economic, social, political and security aspects'.
These matters, she stressed, "require the action of the whole system, according to the principle of economic management by the state, they contain a set of features which place the constitution in the hands of the central government".
She recalled that many countries around the world had already made the digital transition, through government, despite having highly specialised institutions.
It cannot be concluded that the government is interfering with the powers of Congress by issuing the contested decree, because the laws passed by the legislature would be observed", she assured.
The possibility of counting the ballots in Michoacán individually is being considered
According to PREP, the difference between first and second place in the governor's election is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 still to be counted.
The possibility of individual ballot counting is a reality in this year's elections in Michoacán, where according to data from the Programa de Resultados Electorales Preliminares (PREP), the difference between first and second place in the gubernatorial elections is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 still to be counted.
In this context, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just last November 9th, the Electoral Commission had adopted a series of regulations to harmonise local regulations with the reforms of the federal states in electoral matters.
It should be recalled that Michoacán had not adapted its political constitution, its electoral law or its law on electoral justice to the reforms adopted by the Congress, so that they had not entered into force at this election.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) ruled on the constitutional complaint filed by the local legislature, judging the vote of the State Ombudsman on the constitutional reforms as "invalid and unlawful" as he does not have the right to "decide or veto" it.
In an interview on the possibility of individual counting of votes, María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained that thanks to the adoption of the guidelines by the Consejo General del IEM, it would now be possible for the local electoral authority to count the ballots in part or in full.
The results of the minutes are not consistent; the minutes on the counting and calculation of votes are not available on file or are not in the possession of the Chairman of the Electoral Commission or there are obvious errors or changes in the minutes.
In addition, the total number of completed ballots may be counted if there is a difference of one percent or less between the presumed winner and the second-place candidate, provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express request from the party or coalition chairman who is the second of the candidates mentioned.
The total number of votes may also be counted if, after the ordinary counting, it is established that the difference between the presumed winner and the candidate in second place is equal to or less than one percent, provided that this is expressly requested by a representative of the party whose candidate came second.
It is worth noting that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation, where according to PREP the difference between first and second place is just 0.16 percent, although the votes of 129 out of a total of 923 electoral minutes have not yet been counted.
His last will and testament
His ashes will be scattered over the Zapalinamé Mountains, the family confirmed.
The remains of the pilot Felipe Bacio Cortés landed on his birthplace of Saltillo on Sunday evening, followed by a funeral and mass on Monday.
According to family members, the last will of the lieutenant colonel was that his ashes be scattered over the Zapalinamé Mountains.
After a tribute, the family of Bacio Cortés, along with the other victims of the crash, returned to the capital of Coahuila in a Mexican Air Force plane, and those closest to the colonel attended the ceremony in Campo Marte.
At noon, the lieutenant colonel's ashes landed in the funeral home on Nazario Ortiz Garza Boulevard, where family and friends gathered.
At 5:30 p.m., his remains were examined at the Saltillo Institute of Technology, and the funeral was organized by his former students from the technical high school and his American football team, which Felipe Bacio was a member of while preparing for high school.
"He wanted to return to Saltillo and have his ashes scattered over the Zapalinamé mountains, as he had always told his family and friends", said Sandra Bacio Cortés, the pilot's sister.
In her view, the Lieutenant Colonel had fulfilled all his dreams and she believes that he had been at the height of his life. "He was a successful man, exceptional as a father and as a son, a loving brother and he always stood up for his family".
Felipe Bacio Cortés left Saltillo very young to enter the Air Force School of Zapopán, Jalisco.
Some people could not believe it, saying that he would be dizzy even on a truck, but he always aspired to become a pilot.
His nephew Jorge Alberto Dávila Bacio remembers him as a good man. "He had barely arrived in Saltillo, and the whole family wanted to welcome him, as on the occasion when he brought Martha Sahagún to Saltillo".
The young man remembers that even at the age of seven he had gone to Zapopán to attend the graduation of his family member, so he knows that his uncle died while doing what he loved best: flying an airplane.
One last goodbye
The honor was bestowed upon the Mexican Air Force Lieutenant Colonel Felipe Bacio Cortés, under the leadership of Governor Jorge Torres López, by the people and the government, the Mexican Army of the Sixth Military District, the Mexican Air Force, the school principal and students of the Saltillo Institute of Technological Education, where he studied in 1985 and excelled in both studies and sports.
Bacio Cortés died a few days ago when the helicopter he was flying, which also carried Secretary of State José Francisco Blake Mora and six other people from the same authority, crashed.
At 6:05 p.m., the cremated remains of Bacio Cortés, a Saltillo resident, arrived to be handed over by the funeral home to members of the Mexican Air Force, led by Major Jaime Martinez, in the front yard of the barracks, where he was already being awaited by his family, including his daughter Amanda and his wife Cristina, his mother, siblings and other relatives, students and teachers.
