The new Italian government is set to be formed on Wednesday.
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet the President of Italy tomorrow to present the new government to deal with the crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet the President of Italy tomorrow to present the new government to deal with the crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with the president, Giorgio Napolitano, on Wednesday to confirm the formation of the government.
It is expected that he will introduce a majority technocratic cabinet, although it is not yet clear when the new prime minister will take office.
Monti said he would present the President with the results of the talks with the political parties on the formation of the government.
"I want to reaffirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to cope with these difficult times", the former EU commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly confirm the formation of the government, but his comments show that the obstacles have been overcome.
"The frame is well-stitched now", he added.
Monti has managed to form a government in less than three days, which is much less time than usual, while Italy is struggling with a political and financial crisis that has pushed the cost of its debt to unbearable levels.
The new government, led by former EU Commissioner Monti, must pass a tough austerity package demanded by European politicians to regain the lost confidence in Italy.
The pressure on Monti to act quickly was compounded by the volatile market situation, which resulted in Italian government bonds being subject to a 10-year interest rate of 7%, which is the same as the situation in which Greece and Ireland were forced to apply for the European rescue aid.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of the Italian Confederation of Industry, told the press after a meeting with Monti: 'We said we would support this government with all our might.'
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency.
Montis' chances of success have been greatly increased by the support of the PDL party of Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday as a result of the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined to produce good results", said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party.
The support of the PDL, the largest party in Italy, is essential, because so far many of its members have spoken out against a majority technocratic government that Monti is forming.
Support from Parliament
The new Monti government needs strong parliamentary support to implement the likely unpopular austerity measures.
Opposition to its efforts or delaying reforms could bring about another devastating attack by financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks is also pressing for a disaster, saying that Montis's failure is a disaster.
Monti began his debate on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business associations, as well as youth and women's organisations.
The round of meetings should be closed on Tuesday evening.
Monti was appointed this Sunday by Napolitano, who has initiated an extremely rapid change of government in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it was announced that Berlusconi would step down, the cost of Italian government bonds has again reached critical levels due to uncertainty about the success of the new prime minister.
A bailout of Italy with a national debt of 1.8 trillion euros would be too much for the current EU bailout.
Monti said his government would have to last until the next elections, which are expected to be held in 2013, despite predictions that politicians would only give him time to implement reforms instead of preferring elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that it should be made up of technicians only, a sign of their concerns about the procedure imposed by the pressures of the financial markets.
Political sources indicate that the mutual distrust and disagreements between the parties make it difficult to involve people from political life.
