The quintet included Costa Rica in its tour to celebrate its 20th anniversary
"Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In the exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament says the band is preparing to play one of their best shows at National Stadium next Sunday.
They've been waiting for more than 20 years, but the band assures them that when they play in Costa Rica, it's a dream come true for them.
This was confirmed by the bassist and co-founder of the group, Jeff Ament, who gave Viva an exclusive interview from Brazil last week.
The band is in the South American portion of their tour to celebrate their 20th anniversary and on Sunday, the 20th, they will make their only stop in Central America.
On that day, they will perform at the National Stadium starting at 7:30 p.m. with the band The X from Los Angeles and Las Robertas from Costa Rica.
You are reading an excerpt from the conversation, the full text of which can be found in the online edition of La Nación.
For your Costa Rican fans, when Pearl Jam plays in Costa Rica, it's a dream come true: Do you realize what that means for your fans?
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is only the second time we've played in South and Central America, and so far it's been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once on vacation. It's such a beautiful country that we're sure to stay there for a few more days.
We're excited to bring our music there.
I'm asking you this because the fans of the band are completely devoted, and they experience the days leading up to the concert most intensely.
What do you say to your most enthusiastic fans?
Thank you for being by our side all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica, so thank you for waiting so long, and we're sorry it took us so long to get here.
Some people even think your concert is going to be the biggest show of the year.
Doesn't that put a little pressure on your visit?
Some of the greatest shows we've done in the last 21 years have been in the last two weeks.
We've played a few huge shows in Sao Paulo and we hope they've got us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
Really, we're in the mood to play there.
We love this country, we love surfing, we love the jungle, and that's why Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its surf waves?
A lot of our friends are surfers, and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo, where the waves are just unimaginable.
My friends used to go surfing in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, and together with Mexico, they're great places to surf, and that's how we learned about people who love to surf.
Looking at the tour, you've put on some huge shows with a lot of songs.
What are your plans for the event in Costa Rica?
We've never played there before, so we don't set any limits.
We're going to try to give the best show possible with a lot of different songs, we're going to play a few songs from each album and give our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
Why? Why?
I think part of the reason is that we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs, and everybody likes a different song, so deciding which one we're going to play is not easy.
If we add two or three songs that we haven't played in a while, we can better maintain our concentration and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked those songs.
It makes the show more interesting for us and I think it makes it more interesting for the audience.
This tour is a celebration of 20 years of your history.
Looking back, do you find it hard to believe that you've succeeded?
Yeah, totally.
First of all, I don't think any of us ever imagined playing in a great rock band for over 20 years, and it feels like a dream.
We continue to rely on that blessing and are thrilled to be able to make music together again.
We like each other and we're passionate about making music.
We're lucky to be able to go to places in the world we've always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't be better.
What did it mean to you to be actively involved in the birth of the Grunge?
It's always been an honor to be in this group of great bands.
We're good friends with the people at Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It's surprising and quite unusual when a movement comes from a group of friends.
Occasionally a band comes out of a city, but it is not uncommon for five or ten groups to come out of the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we went to a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on tour, and we're excited to still be friends with all of them and it's an honor to be part of this emerging Seattle sound.
It's also very unusual for a band like yours to have been with the same musicians for so long.
Yeah, the four of us have been playing together for 21 years, and Matt joined us 13 years ago, which is a lot longer than most bands last.
First of all, I think we're all lucky to be alive and, besides, we care about each other.
We're all close friends, which is why musical avenues have opened up that give each individual the freedom to experiment.
We know each other and their music, and we couldn't be better.
Your relationship with fame has not always been easy, but on the other hand, thanks to your success, you've always been able to do what you wanted.
How do you find a balance?
The way we've grown has made it easier for us to find balance.
We make sure we don't go on tour too much, because it's too easy to fall for this game with huge crowds who love your music.
As long as you remember that people came for music, it reminds you that you have to care about music and what it brought to life, without being obsessed with being a famous rock star.
What are your memories of your other project, Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote some really good songs and it was great at first.
We were a band for three years, never releasing a record until Andy [Andrew Woods] died.
We were disappointed that it took so long, and we're still good friends with Bruce [Fairweather] and Greg [Gilmore], who built the band with us, and every time I hear a song or see a picture, I think about what an incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh, and it was always a joy to go to work, laughing together and talking about music and football and many other things.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The local band Las Robertas are responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose the band for the opening?
Yeah, the production team sent us videos of several bands, and we liked this one the best, so we're curious to see what Las Robertas has to offer live.
Why do you always change the lyrics to Yellow Ledbetter when you play it live?
That's a question for Ed, I have no idea.
He sings it, and I think he sings the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who influenced you as a bassist?
Of so many
The first people I can think of are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There's so many I could talk all afternoon about the bass players I like.
How did Pearl Jam keep the grunge alive when it was no longer a fad?
I don't think we all feel very connected to the word grunge.
When I think about it, I think of the bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana, and all the other bands that came out at the same time, and if they're still relevant today, I think that's great, because it's worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are making better music than ever.
At first, her music was darker, but now it's more positive.
Why? Why?
That's interesting because I think there are a few songs on the new album that might seem a little light-hearted, but there are also other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, even though they have some positive things in them.
I cried when I heard Ed play them, both of them.
I think that when you get older and something traumatic happens in your life -- like losing a family member or a friend -- it affects your artistic work and your music, and these two songs are very much a reflection of that for me.
But I also believe that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
Peru:
Fujimori was taken back to the hospital for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to be examined for muscle loss in his legs, his family doctor said.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving a 25-year sentence for human rights violations during his rule (1990-2000), has several medical conditions, including tongue cancer, which has been operated on four times and is under control.
Alejandro Aguinaga, a congressman and his personal physician, told television that Fujimori would be examined for three days at the Peruvian Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neoplásicas hospital to determine the cause of his pain and muscle loss in his lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that he thought Fujimori could be pardoned on humanitarian grounds, but he did not want to do so because he considered him innocent.
He had four surgeries for tongue cancer and had lost 18 pounds, plus other conditions, including severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure, and circulatory problems in his legs, the doctor said.
Fujimori has been detained since September 2007 in the Directorate National of Special Police Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the Peruvian army's death squad, which operated underground during his government.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation led by Uruguayan President José Mujica, composed of several ministers and businessmen, will begin their visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss regional political issues.
Mujica is due to meet his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calderón next Wednesday, which, according to the Uruguayan president, will be the culmination of his busy schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the collective of Uruguayans living in Mexico.
The meeting between the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara "is a good opportunity for the exchange of information on all policy areas between the two countries", the South American country's presidential office said on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is seeking Calderón's support over the incident with France when French Prime Minister Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on a tax haven list at the G20 summit in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Mr Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries which still appear to be tax havens, a statement which was rejected by Uruguay and prompted a request from his ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group of the world's most powerful emerging and industrialized countries, and has had an agreement with the South American country since January on the exchange of tax information to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguay Round of the Uruguay Round of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) was held in Brussels on 15 and 16 March.
On the business side, a free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay has been in place since 2004, which has contributed to the growing trade in goods between the two countries.
The moustache-wielding installer enters the third dimension with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has been fighting tirelessly for 25 years to rescue Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but never in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land", he fights for the love of the girl in stereo technology.
The game, which is coming to stores around the world this month, was tailored from the start to the features of the Nintende 3DS handheld console, which allows for three-dimensional play without special glasses.
"Mario is the figure who has to tell how stereoscopy works without glasses", assured Omar Álvarez, the head of the Nintendo-specialized press in Spain at the presentation of the video game in Madrid.
Álvarez stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" was "the first video game from Nintendo to be developed from scratch for this console", because until now, success stories like "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of existing titles.
The Nintendo spokesperson emphasized that although it is three-dimensional, Super Mario 3D Land is an "affordable" video game that allows for fast, fluid play.
Álvarez confirmed that "Super Mario 3D Land" contained two games in one: The first part is "easy" to capture the less shy users.
After that, the experts can take a "second round" of the increasingly difficult game levels.
In addition, users can choose in real time between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action.
This trip of Super Mario to the three-dimensional world also means the return of the figure to a portable console, which has not been the case since 2005.
With this video game, Nintendo winked at the fans of the saga and repeated the recipe for success of the last issues: The mustachioed installer must overcome platforms dotted with dangers to free Princess Peach.
However, the player encounters new moves, environment, disguises, and enemies - and a "playable" Luigi.
Colom guarantees the delivery of Portillos to the United States
The President of Guatemala, Álvaro Colom, announced on Tuesday that he would extradite former Governor Alfonso Portillo to face charges in the United States for the US$70 million money laundering conspiracy.
The trial ends with the US requesting Portillo's extradition so that he can be tried there.
In a press conference, Colom confirmed that his decision was based on the independence of the judiciary and government, taking into account that an extradition was already ordered by a court.
He stressed that during his administration he did not interfere in judicial decisions and granted all extradition requests of which he was informed.
In addition to Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín will be extradited for murder and grievous bodily harm, Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
Colom's action is a governmental act, which takes place when all the judicial and constitutional authorities have been exhausted to convict the former president (2000-2004).
According to the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court of Guatemala, Portillo must be extradited once his legal situation in Guatemala is clarified and his human rights guaranteed.
Portillo was acquitted of the embezzlement of 120 million Quetzales in the Ministry of Defense during his administration, a trial that preceded the extradition, but the Minister objected and re-invigorated the case.
Trinijove has helped 6000 young people at risk of social exclusion
The organisation was set up to prevent the marginalization of young people without vocational training.
The first 25 years of the Trinijove social assistance organisation have produced important results: during this quarter of a century, 6000 young people threatened by social exclusion have been helped to find a way out of their difficult situation.
In addition, more than 100 jobs have been created for this social group.
On the occasion of the anniversary, a review was carried out yesterday at an event in the former factory buildings of Fabra i Coats, attended by over 300 people.
Trinijove was founded in 1986 in the Trinitat Vella district with the aim of helping young people with low levels of education, unemployed, drug-related problems and at risk of marginalization.
Yesterday's celebration in Sant Andreu was attended by many leaders of institutions and institutions that have worked with the association for 25 years.
The participation of political representatives of different orientations during election campaigns demonstrated the impartiality of Trinijove's work.
Apart from the President of the Generalitat (Parliament of the Autonomous Region of Catalonia), Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol, the former Socialist Minister of Education, Ernest Maragall, and the former mayor and now left-green city councillor, Ricard Goma, took part in the celebrations.
The great hall of Fabra i Coats was also visited by the current Catalan Minister for Social Affairs and the Family, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the Director-General of the Social Work Department of the La Caixa Savings Bank, Jaume Lanaspa.
Mas stressed that Trinijove was created in very difficult times and that the present times are no less complicated, but he added that the work done so far is "a good foundation".
For the President of the Generalitat, Trinijove is an example of a man who knows how to fight against difficult circumstances and gives hope to people in difficulty.
"The economic crisis is nothing new for the association and the work it does", he explained.
Occupied house where huge parties were held was cleared
The owners occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building at 51 Balmes Street (Barcelona).
The 12 occupants left the building yesterday afternoon without resistance.
Everything indicates that the nightmares of the neighbors of the house No. 51 on Balmes Street have come to an end.
Twelve people voluntarily left the building yesterday at noon, which they had illegally occupied and where they had organized huge parties that had driven the neighborhood to despair.
After the evacuation, the door lock was replaced to avoid a similar situation.
"From now on, access will be controlled", the house manager confirmed.
The occupants, who occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building - the rest were occupied - took all the electrical equipment and part of the water supply, painted the walls, and left behind all kinds of trash, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
In the three lower floors, huge parties were held, lasting up to two days, driving the tenants to despair.
Next to the building is a discotheque, Balmes 51, which also suffered damage.
Their owner, Maria Pantinat, told Europa Press that their business had declined by 80% since the start of the occupation.
The owner of the disco pointed out that the tenants were unfairly competing, selling the drinks for three euros, whereas in the disco they cost 10 euros.
The owner of the club had also been denounced by neighbours for disturbing her sleep, while she claimed that the noise was not caused by the disco patrons but by the occupants of the house and in particular by the guests of the parties that were held there, which according to the angry neighbours had been increasing and prolonging in recent weeks.
The manager of the disco explained that the harassment was so great that she agreed with the owner of the building not to have to pay rent for the last nine months.
The Guardia Urbana (city police) also confirmed that they have received more complaints from neighbors in recent weeks.
The chairman of the PP (Partido Popular - People's Party) in Barcelona's city council, Alberto Fernández Díaz, last week called for the building to be evacuated immediately and for the problems of civic coexistence and the decline of the neighbourhood to be tackled.
He explained that before the summer, only one floor of the building had been occupied, but that in recent months the occupants had penetrated all floors of the building and almost all apartments, and in some cases even committed theft.
In this sense, he added that "it is necessary to put an end to impunity and to act against the antisocial actions in the building".
Yesterday, another building in the Nou Barris district was evacuated by the Catalan police.
At 3:30 p.m., police approached 35 Montral Street after receiving a call from a neighbor who had observed four people trying to break into the building.
The four were immediately arrested.
Park or mountain?
Apart from the dispute over the fees, the architects are in agreement with the tender.
The city's tender for the 16 gates reopens the debate on the importance of Collserola in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the now-defunct Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this administration published its defamation of the funding of Collserola.
The brochure described the mountain as a huge park in Barcelona city.
It has even been compared in numbers to Central Park in New York.
With the demise of the CMB in 1987, the park was again seen by many as the upper limit of Barcelona, since the capital of Catalonia is one of the few that does not extend in a north-south direction, but upwards (mountains) and downwards (sea).
The designation of Collserola as a nature reserve is in keeping with this idea.
The model was no longer Central Park, but Yellowstone, with wild boars in the role of the yogibars.
This was the case when the city launched a massive tender in September, consisting of 16 competitions, for additional access gates to Collserola.
No doubt a gate refers to the concept of a park.
Either that's the case, or someone's planning to put gates on the land.
The question is: Collserola, park or mountain?
The call for tenders is not only an organizational issue, but also a topic of discussion for all Barcelona architects, as it is a reflection on the city.
It is almost a recurring theme that two members of this old-fashioned caste can draw on when they meet in the elevator.
And this very fact provides the material for one of the rare coincidences between what three architects in Barcelona think about it and some university professors who have applied for the project.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: The call for tenders is appropriate.
Roldán said that after the attack on the coast, "it is necessary" to speak of the "front on the mountain", insofar as the discourse of Ildefons Cerda, which was about the green apples, has not been delivered.
"It should be assumed that the beach is the largest park in Barcelona.
One reason is that it's easily accessible.
Collserola is more complex", says the architect, for whom the title "Gates of Collserola" is a "lexical trap": one must not think of them "as entrances to a park, but as the boundaries of areas where action is required".
Modol, like Roldán and Bayona, who have experience in urban planning, sees the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" which carries "some dangers".
The Commission has also been asked to examine the potential of the new technologies in the area of public transport, which are now being used in the Community.
The first fear is one's own limitation on what can be built.
"To limit something is always to set the next step", that is, to go beyond it.
"We must think about new urban planning instruments, because the current ones [in relation to the Plan General Metropolitano (PGM) ] can lead to a real catastrophe".
Modol, who is more specific, says that the side of Collserola that goes towards Vallesana "can be understood as a park that does not go towards Barcelona", for purely topographical reasons.
Modol recalls that there is already a study by Patronat de Collserola that should not "be a surprise", although he is grateful to the city administration for giving his committee the opportunity to participate in this project "from the very beginning".
He also notes that the proximity of the mountain to the city is the guiding letter that allows architects to participate in the debate, although he expresses his "doubts" about whether this technical profile should guide the multidisciplinary teams created ("just the right thing", he says) "We architects should be just a tool".
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question in the title of this article is complex, since the tender conditions lack a global view of Collserola: "There were 16 cross-sectional competitions", he says, "on the mountain-sea axis. But there is no longitudinal perspective that looks at the area as a whole".
At least in his case, that's what got him into the 16 contests.
Otherwise, the program and the definition of a gate project would conflict with that of the architect of the gate next door.
In his view, it is essential that the city guarantee that the strip directly above the Ronda de Dalt is equipped along its entire length in such a way as to allow a smooth transition between the city and the green areas.
Casino forgives Jonás Larrazábal, who is released
After 72 days of silence, the attorney general of the Red Casino has released the brother of the mayor of Monterrey from the trial against him for alleged extortion.
After 72 days in detention, Manuel Jonás Larrazábal is released after the Casino Red's attorney pardoned him before the Second District Criminal Court, which is prosecuting the brother of the mayor of Monterrey for extortion.
After the attack on the Casino Royale, Sergio Gil García, the owner of the Casino Red, published a series of photos and videos showing Manuel Jonás, who allegedly forces him to pay a sum of money so that the city administration would approve the secret operation of the bookmaker.
After the criminal complaint, the prosecutor's office opened a criminal case against the brother of the Panist mayor, who was detained for 30 days on September 2.
After four hours with the official of the Ministerio Público 3 en Delitos Patrimoniales, he was taken to Casa de Arraigo 1 in the Barrio Antiguo of the capital.
He remained there for 49 days after a second arrest warrant was issued after the official of the Ministerio Público had denied the charges of bribery and organized crime.
On October 19, he was transferred to the Cadereyta prison for allegedly bribing the owners of the Red Casino with one and a half million pesos, but he only stayed a few hours in the medium security detention center because of death threats.
The authorities allowed him to attend the trial as a prisoner in the municipal prison of San Nicolás de los Garza.
