This Monday, the attorney general of Casino Red, Víctor Aldo García Gómez, asked the judge José Luis Pecina, the mayor's brother, to waive the sentence, which is why he will be released in the next few hours.
During the court hearing, Ramiro Arias, an official of the Ministerio Público attached to the court, asked García Gómez whether he had repaired the damage and which of the owners of the betting house had expressed his forgiveness, but the lawyer did not name him.
In accordance with Case 197/2011, Jonás Larrazábal is acquitted, and no further appeals against the trial can be lodged, nor is any claim for damages made.
After hearing the authorized agent of the bookmaker at about 15:50 Larrazabal Bretón was immediately released.
The court clerk, Jorge Yánez, went to the municipal prison of San Nicolás de los Garza to inform Jonás that he had been acquitted and his case would be filed.
He also informed him of the court order for his immediate release.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash that killed Secretary of State Francisco Blake and seven others.
The Secretaría de Comunicaciones y Transportes - SCT (Mexican Secretariat of Communications and Transport) reported that the investigation into the accident that killed government secretary Francisco Blake Mora and seven others indicated that the helicopter, with its entire intact structure, crashed directly into the ground without the pilot being able to initiate an emergency landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary for Communications and Transport, mentioned that the pilot had confirmed before take-off that the weather conditions were suitable for the flight.
"The fact that the propeller wings were in contact with trees at 25 meters, with the helicopter losing its fuselage, seems to indicate that the helicopter had several ground contacts".
He also stated that the helicopter was built for 19 passengers and therefore met all the requirements for the transport of personnel.
He also said that the search of the area where the plane had crashed had found no helicopter parts.
"The search did not find any aircraft parts elsewhere, the attack affected the entire structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 passengers, so it met all the requirements for passenger transport.
The area has an inclination of 7 to 30 degrees.
At the moment, the priority is to get the results as soon as possible, but this could take several months, perhaps even a year.
Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Aeropuertos y Servicios Auxiliares (Secretariat of Aircraft and Auxiliary Services in Mexico), assured that the helicopter from the Estado Mayor Presidencial was flying at cruising speed when it hit the ground and the plane had fallen on a soft slope.
"This information reinforces the assumption that at the time of the collision, this was a normal flight operation".
At a press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant points to be taken into account in the investigation:
The flight of sight:
In accordance with flight rules, this was a flight in accordance with the rules of visual flight, which means that the crew must have had sufficient visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The AICM recorded favorable weather conditions at the time of take-off, and as it continued toward the border area between Mexico City and the State of Mexico, some deep hanging clouds were lifted.
Routes selected:
It is possible that the crew chose a lower area with better visibility toward the Cuernavaca Valley because of the clouds.
The impact site:
The collision coordinates and the last radar recording of the helicopter match, and it's possible that there was no loss of control of the aircraft or deviation from the flight path prior to the collision.
Dispersion of the aircraft debris in a restricted area:
The information available to date suggests that the helicopter was impacted from a straight and lateral direction.
The pattern of scattered aircraft debris suggests that the helicopter was struck on the ground with its structure intact.
No sign of fire or explosion.
The remains of the plane at the crash site show no evidence of fire or explosion.
The latest results of the investigation indicate several ground contacts.
The site survey found aircraft parts at an altitude of 9,200 feet above sea level, in a sloping terrain with an inclination of seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter probably broke down.
Some information suggests that the helicopter may have had multiple ground contacts.
After a thorough search of an area beyond the restricted area at the crash site, no scattered aircraft parts could be found, reinforcing the assumption that the unharmed aircraft structure had crashed into the ground.
MSS announces research protocol to find the gene for obesity
The Social Security Institute of Mexico is leading a research project to find the gene for childhood and adolescent obesity, supported by specialists from the IPN.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Mexican Social Insurance Institute) announced that it is leading a research project to discover the gene for obesity in children and adolescents, entitled "Genetics of childhood and adolescence obesity", to find the genetic markers associated with overweight.
Miguel Cruz López, head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Department of Medical Research, with a focus on Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, said that an interdisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) of the Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The public is invited to participate in the study, and interested parties can come to the IMSS sports grounds in the Valley of Mexico, where tests are carried out on children and adolescents every Saturday from 8 a.m.
He stressed that the investigation had started at the Cuauhtémoc sports ground (in the west of the State of México) and was continuing since 8 October at the Nezahualcóyolt sports ground (in the east of the State of México).
When the target of 500 to 600 subjects is reached, the study will be continued at the Independencia sports ground (in the south of the capital) and completed at the Morelos ground (in the north of the capital).
He explained that the aim of the study was to identify the factors and the role of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and adolescents for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On World Diabetes Day, he said, the goal is to get 3,000 children and adolescents between the ages of six and 14 to complete nutrition questionnaires with their parents' consent and supervision.
They are also asked about their physical activity and family history of disease to control risk factors that may lead to diabetes or kidney failure.
He also explained that on those Saturdays, subjects were measured (weight, height, waist circumference), their blood pressure was checked and blood levels such as glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (an attempt to identify genes associated with childhood obesity) were determined.
Cruz López stressed that this study was being conducted in response to the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight gain among young people.
"The health surveys conducted in 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years the proportion of obese boys increased by 77 percent and that of obese girls by 47 percent, and that overweight also increased dramatically", the IMSS specialist said.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the people of Mexico differed from that of other peoples.
He stated that a Mexican is on average 65 percent Native American, 30 percent European, and 5 percent African, which is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
Generally, he explained, the genetics of obesity are expressed in the inability to burn the excess energy (calories) taken in, so that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to the study participants would be a comprehensive examination of the children to determine whether they were overweight or obese.
It would even look at the occurrence of dark skin folds on the neck and forearm (akanthosis), which indicate the likelihood of metabolic disorders and early diabetes.
All information would be kept confidential and communicated to the parents in writing by the doctors, who would explain to the parents all the results of the tests and suggest lifestyle changes that are appropriate for preventing disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three basic factors that are responsible for overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: lack of exercise, that is, lack of exercise in everyday life, spending most of the day in front of the TV, and using transportation instead of walking short distances.
The high calorie intake, i.e. increased consumption of sugary drinks and carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) together with a high fat and protein intake, and the genetics to be analysed in this research project.
Asphalt from UNAM prevents blowholes
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the University of Mexico, UNAM, has developed polymer-modified asphalt to make the mixture more resistant to weather and temperature fluctuations
If the signs emanating from the pavement were taken into account, it would not be necessary to repair almost 200 000 potholes when the rainy season starts in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México, said Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM University, warning that if the asphalt pavement is properly laid out and maintained, the number of potholes would be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his presentation on "Strike Holes from a Technical Point of View" at the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing polymer-modified asphalt to produce a mixture similar to asphalt but with greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera felt that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behaviour of the road surface and thus avoid the appearance of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of petroleum, is a hydrocarbon compound, one part of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphaltene - and the other part a low one - the so-called malthene.
The asphalt's saelastic behaviour means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, is very tough at 120°C and almost solid at 50°C, while it becomes brittle at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes over a day depending on weather conditions and temperature fluctuations", explained the chemical engineer.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City had a majority of flexible pavement, consisting of six layers of material, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the upper layers lies a layer of asphalt, which is made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone in this layer of wear and tear has been bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles move on it and forces are generated, this layer allows for good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed", said the chemical engineer.
"Over the wear layer", he explained, "a final layer is laid, the so-called support layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which has also been bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, it requires a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and must produce friction.
This pavement, which receives and distributes the most forces, also needs a suitable thickness of the supporting layer and the material from which it is made.
Weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature variations, are other important factors to consider, especially water", he said, "because it significantly affects the wear behaviour of the layer.
When the terrain becomes wet, water enters the layer and is difficult to get out of it, softening all layers of the road surface and resulting in the appearance of puncture holes.
"When a hole is made", he said, "the roof is first removed, and the wear layer is only affected afterwards. But the damage is not immediate, but is a process that should be maintained at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs".
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (Mexican National Research System) explained that vehicle load was another important cause of puncture holes, so the thickness of each layer of road surface should always be in proportion to the vehicle load and it should be ensured that this rule is followed to avoid frequent puncture holes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that much research was still to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which were already on the market in other countries and which could be used to repair the puncture holes easily and without the use of high temperatures.
