So was the work of the doctor who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A California lophoscopist went down in history as the man who identified "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is key.
On November 4, a Lophoscopist from the Investigative Unit of the Public Prosecutor's Office (CTI) in Cali went in as the man who confirmed the identity of the FARC leader: "Alfonso Cano" by comparing fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopists in the CTI department, this week's on call was Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in criminal investigations for 21 years.
Early in his career, González worked in communities in Chocó, where he often had to walk for five days through the jungle to reach the location of the bodies he was supposed to identify.
In 2000 he moved to Valle and after completing the required courses he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin that is subject to friction, i.e. the hands and feet.
During the week of the operation against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was told to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
Friday night he flew in a helicopter from Palmira to Cauca.
He knew he had to identify two bodies, and that there was a suspicion that one might be that of the man who had led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he had to take the fingerprint sheet of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he and the examiner reached the location of the body, he could not identify it because of its physical appearance, which was not in the least similar to the images he had seen in the mass media.
He had no beard, was dressed like a local farmer, wore no glasses, and was much thinner.
But fingerprints are not a lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a plant cell, and a flashlight, Eleazar compared the prints on the body with those on the printing plate.
He saw right, it was "Alfonso Cano".
That very night, this man from Puerto Tejada was responsible for telling the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was indeed the head of the FARC.
Searching for clues
For a dactyloscope from Sijín in Cali, the recognition given by President Juan Manuel Santos to Eliazar González at a press conference on the operation against "Cano" was very important.
A lot of people don't know what we do.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science with no error rate, which can be a key factor in solving a crime.
Loposcopists not only identify bodies, they also assist in murder and robbery investigations and confirm the identity of those arrested.
Many criminals present false identity papers when they are arrested or do not have any.
We'll take their fingerprints and run them through the database.
The investigator told us that in one theft, he had to tear a piece of the wall out of a house, because the thief had stood up with his hand at that exact spot when he pulled out a safe filled with jewelry and money.
"Walls are difficult because their surfaces are not suitable for fingerprinting, but in this case we were able to take the fingerprint of the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in several thefts", he recalled.
Fingerprints can also be used to exonerate or incriminate murder suspects.
Recently, a dead man was found surrounded by liquor bottles.
The investigation suggested that a family member might be a suspect, and in fact, a fingerprint on the bottle was a match.
Although this does not guarantee that the murderer is the killer, it does link him to the place where the crime was committed.
A CTI dactyloscopist explained that "the fingerprints would be taken from the object with chemical or physical reagents".
When they appear, a plant cell or tape is used to take them away.
Then the prints are sent to Asif, which is the crime database, or the personnel office.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians without identification papers", explained the CTI expert.
He said that not everything was as it was portrayed in the TV series SCI.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, not everything you touch is a fingerprint.
But it can still be used if you make a comparison.
