For several days now, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and their supporters have been making their thunderous statements and their statements about the traditional Republican focus on the open air.
China, Iran and aid to Israel are all covered in slogans, often without any substantiation.
Mitt Romney, the most vocal on the appointment of the "Grand Old Party", threatened to take the Chinese to the WTO and accuse them of "currency manipulation" - a leading issue in an America that is most irritated by the emigration of entire industries to Asia.
He said it was foolish to imply that this would lead to a trade war.
Jon Huntsman, former ambassador to China under Obama and the only candidate who seems to have a mature vision of foreign policy, has almost shut down about his emotionally flattering gesture.
He had called for a firm but constructive dialogue with Beijing (also the current stance of Obama).
But Huntsman is not being heard, stagnating in the depths of the polls.
The image of Reagan
Romney had also promised military strikes against Iran if the sanctions to stop the nuclear program failed.
"If I am elected, I will stop Iran", he had said.
"If Obama is re-elected, they'll get the bomb".
He also promised increased military aid to Israel and accused Obama of defaulting on his commitments to that partner.
The second-ranked candidate, businessman Herman Cain, is also showing a shameful lack of knowledge of the file.
He recently called for a counter-measure to the Chinese military threat as Beijing "attempts to develop a nuclear power" - and seemed to overlook the fact that China has had military nuclear weapons since 1964!
Texas Governor Rick Perry, who supports Israel and calls for military strikes against Iran, has expressed his willingness to deploy the U.S. military in Mexico to fight drug cartels.
The 2009 Obama ban on the use of torture against suspected terrorists was also supported by Cain, Perry and candidate Michele Bachmann.
It is a far cry from John McCain, the Republican candidate in 2008, who is a political heavyweight.
Unlike the current presidential opponents, Reagan had also had simple ideas and won the Cold War despite all of them.
They remind us that Obama himself was an amateur and had to pour water into his wine when it came to the issue of counterterrorism.
They rightly insist on the failure of his naive two-way talks with Iran, the premature withdrawal of his "boys" from Iraq, his indecision in Libya, which also earned him the reputation of weakness.
This hostility is not entirely unforced.
The public is more likely to appreciate the positive record of national security under Obama, which took out bin Laden.
Since Iraq, it has been guarding against military intervention leading to paralysis.
And Obama surprisingly more aptly argues that America needs to rebuild economically to revive its leadership.
Nord Stream, the new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects Western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is designed to supply the equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with glamour.
More than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline, which links Russia and Germany directly under sea level, on the Baltic coast last Tuesday, to orchestral accompaniment and a fine-tasting buffet.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have symbolically turned the steering wheel of the valve that will carry Russian gas to the Western European grid.
The new gas pipeline is intended to supply 27,5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas per year to Western Europe via an initial 1,224 km pipeline linking the St. Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania.
A second pipeline, which will allow a total supply of 55 billion cubic metres of gas - equivalent to total French consumption - is due to be completed by the end of 2012.
And the possibility of a third line being built on the same line is already being hinted at.
The timely and accurate completion of this enormous construction project is a victory for Gazprom.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord Stream pipeline will allow direct gas supply to Germany, avoiding any route through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) by land.
The European Union has been a major player in the development of the region, and the European Union has been a major contributor to the development of the region.
Warsaw, the most involved in the debate, was not shy about comparing the Nord Stream pipeline to a "new German-Soviet pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the subject is politically extremely sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by supporting this Russian project.
But this is at the expense of a disempowerment of European energy, as the project has cut a gap between Western and Eastern Europe.
Russia has managed in less than five years to implement its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries with high gas consumption and dwindling gas reserves.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way", François Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of the pipeline, pointing out the political and economic importance of major gas contracts.
All this explains the broad smiles of the Gazprom managers, who are very numerous in Lubmin, when it comes to the gas pipeline.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater pipe is made of steel with a concrete casing to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at a depth of about 200 meters.
The construction of the new facilities was designed to avoid the use of World War II-era minefields.
"About a hundred mines had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution", said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, more measures were needed to protect the fauna and flora.
The cable is a long metal snake, as heavy as 242 Eiffel Towers, which is uninterrupted by anything along its length: neither valves nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the Swedish coast, but the project was abandoned because the Swedes were not keen to see a Russian state-owned company permanently established on their shores.
"In the event of an accident, we close the gas leak in less than a minute", Jens Müller explained.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the gas line will escape into the air.
However, this is considered by the designers to be unlikely, since the welding seams have been estimated to have a leakage rate of one per 100,000 years.
State control of the gas pipeline is provided by both an underwater robot controlled from a seagoing vessel for external observation purposes and a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It is shaped like a cigar, has a diameter of one metre, is inserted into the inside of the pipe and is moved by gas pressure.
After three full days of traveling through the line at a speed of 3 metres per second, the device provides the most accurate information on possible deformation of the metal on arrival.
The gas transmission was designed to run for fifty years without the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is ensured by simple pressure.
This is 200 bar at the point of entry and 100 bar at the point of exit.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
The German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each) are also included, as are Gasunie in the Netherlands and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to this company all of its gas transport capacity on a 20-year renewable contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the volume of gas it actually transports", Jens Müller said.
The financing of the gas pipeline was 30% secured by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of work for both pipelines is expected to be EUR 7.4 billion.
For example, the investment for GDF Suez amounted to 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders were reluctant to recover their costs, as Gazprom alone bears the risk of liability.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea near Lubmin on a sandy, pine-forested stretch of coastline.
The 15 feet high valves form the gas exit gate.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other parameters of the incoming gas before it is passed on to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with one million cubic meters of Russian gas per passing hour.
At full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic metres per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine, a brand notebook. What is it?
Moleskine, who started a company in Italy some 15 years ago, is now trying to give writing a new style.
It has a flair of adventure, candlelight hours spent writing.
Moleskine's notebook is easily recognizable, with its black, rectangular wrapper, its rubber band, the eggshell-colored pages, as if aged over time.
The Moleskine notebook, as we know it today, was created in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, which is based in Milan, decided at that time to launch a distinctive design notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, is responsible for the launch of the new product.
The notebook was inspired by an ancient production technique called mole skin, which refers to a cotton lacquer used, for example, for upholstery benches.
This type of notebook was in great demand among writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has revived an old and almost forgotten object, which until the 20th century was considered an icon of avant-garde artists", explains Maria Sebregondi, now brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success is coming.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% and reached 12,7 million units.
This is a far cry from the usual production of the early years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to get a phantom picture of the buyers, since the notebook is as much a source of excitement for businessmen as for students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of a cosmopolitan, cultured, open-minded client.
The small Italian company, which started with 12 employees, now employs over 100 people and has two offices since 2008, one in Milan and the other in New York.
The company sells its notebooks in bookstores, on internet portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques in the city centres and is keen to assert its identity.
"We have followed the zeitgeist and its new need for writing, which persists despite the surge in e-mails", explained Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural characteristic is accompanied by the development of the company Moleskine: recently the brand launched an exhibition called "Detour", in which architects and artists exhibited their own notebooks.
In August, the company also launched a leopard pattern wrapper for the Locarno Film Festival.
Moleskine benefited from its success and this cultural zeitgeist and was able to diversify its products: bags, calendars, pens, computer cases... The brand has the full range of items.
A success that aroused jealousy: in the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, thus opening a new chapter in the history of the company Moleskine.
Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain at such a high level?
Approximately 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
Today is the start of the 15th week of work for the disabled.
Despite a targeted public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people is always twice as high as the average: 19% versus 9% unemployment of the total population.
Discouraging you?
"No", says Éric Blanchet, director-general of the Adapt association, which organises the "Working Week for the Disabled".
"The progress made in fifteen years is considerable".
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not doubled, but tripled".
"Nevertheless, there is still a tremendous amount of work to be done".
It must be said, however, that for disabled unemployed people, numerous obstacles remain before they can find a job.
The elderly are more likely to be affected: 37% are over 50 years of age (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualifications: 80% of them do not have a high school diploma and there are only 10,000 disabled people among the 2.3 million students with a higher education degree.
Finally, longterm unemployment is also widespread: 53% of the disabled compared with 38% on average.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it difficult to re-enter the workforce, and that are "at the heart of the problem", says Christian Grapin, director general of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
So much for the actual brakes.
The unspoken remain, the attitudes that are certain but slow to develop.
A study carried out in April by the IMS Entrepreneurs Association for La Cité magazine found that the managers surveyed had "a low level of knowledge about disabled people", which was "over-represented" by "people in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually handicapped".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to achieve the 6% target of disabled workers, which was set out in a 1987 law.
The latter figures, which date from 2008, refer to a ratio of 2,6%.
"We are now at the 3% mark", says Pierre Blanc, director general of Agefiph, the organization charged with collecting contributions from companies that break the law.
The evidence is that the number of 'feepaying' establishments has decreased, as has the total amount paid, from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros) between 2007 and 2011.
"The 2005 law, which provides for contribution increases, put a lot of pressure on companies", said Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also expresses a real insight, particularly in the case of large groups of companies".
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of enterprises with between 20 and 49 employees employ disabled workers, while enterprises with between 100 and 199 employees employ 82%.
Hazard: "What a stroke of luck".
Even before they faced the "Blue Tuesday evening" at 8:45 p.m., Eden Hazard and Georges Leekens hadn't hidden the pleasure of the friendly match.
It would be too far-fetched to say that there was a secret agreement between them, but the picture speaks of symbolic volumes.
Sitting side by side on the stage of the Stade de France, George Leekens and Eden Hazard could have made peace.
Five months after his attacker's temperamental gesture against Turkey, the Belgian national coach had received nothing but praise for his personality.
"I'm very satisfied with Eden, his progress and the fact that he's Belgian".
"I want to look ahead", assures the native Liller.
As for the contrast between his performance in club and national team, "It's a unity that justifies everything".
"I'm in Lille all year round, which is not the case in Belgium".
"It's time for me to go to the start".
Hazard will be coming to Saint-Denis, bringing in Friday night against Romania for the match against France, to finally "shine".
But without omitting the "pleasure" element.
He has been playing for the French national team since the age of seven, leading the team to victories between 1998 and 2000.
"I was always supported", he said.
This inevitably contributes to reinforcing the 'unique' character of this meeting.
"Mathieu (Debuchy), Yohan (Cabaye) and Adil (Rami) will be there", he said.
"We just crossed paths".
"To play against them is great luck!"
Leekens, for his part, kindly said "Pride".
"Pride of a Galamatch".
"Proud" also to confirm - in its capacity as"neighbour" - that France has "become a team at a very high level again", and this just over a year after the Knysna trauma.
"Laurent Blanc did a damn good job", he said enthusiastically.
Although Belgium will be absent from the next European Championship, the technician is very likely to share the plane with the Blues (the French National team)... to Brazil in 2014.
"We little Belgians are getting along great", he stressed.
"We're planning something, the players are ambitious, they're hungry".
"You'll notice that at the upcoming games, including the game against France.
Portugal very confident
The Portuguese team of Paulo Bento is looking forward to the rematch against Bosnia (22:00 p.m.) this Tuesday in Lisbon with great optimism.
Both teams had been unsuccessful in the game.
"At the end of 90 minutes, we'll be a happy team and, most importantly, a happy country".
Paulo Bento is already in Poland and Ukraine.
He has no doubt that La Selecçao, his national team, for which he has been in charge since September 2010, will qualify for the European Championship 2012.
For Portugal, that is really only 90 minutes of happiness.
But there is one match to be played and one opponent to be eliminated, and that is Bosnia.
Given the 0-0 draw on Friday in Zenica Hell, it seems obvious that the dice have not yet fallen.
Portugal clearly dominated the game for more than an hour, but the team was unable to give the matter the important stamp that would have taken the pressure off it.
"This is a good result, but it carries some risk because we didn't score a goal".
But at home, in their brightly lit Stade de la Luz in Lisbon, the Portuguese are confident of making it in front of an audience that is likely to be equally keen on the game, even if the game was, of course, announced as 'very close', said the optimistic but clear-sighted Bento.
"We expect a very close match, but we are absolutely confident that we can win the game", explained the 42-year-old Portuguese coach.
"We still have a 50% chance of being in the 2012 European Championship", said Carlos Queiroz's successor.
The draw on Friday in Bosnia forces the Portuguese to score and win.
A draw may be enough for the Bosnians, who also need a goal.
"It's a good result, but it's a risk because we didn't score a goal", Bento regrets.
"We will be playing against a team that has high technical qualities and has players with many individual qualities", he added.
As in Zenica, the Portuguese planned to exert maximum pressure on the Bosniaks from the outset, to 'not allow them time to think'.
A good idea, provided it is put into action this time.
